origin.p:
France Paris , 14th century, middle. Roosval (1948) and Avril (1972) place the style of decoration as stemming from the school of Jean Pucelle, who was active at Paris in the early 14th century. Avril identifies the artist as active there in the middle of the 14th century. Avril does not lend any credence to the addition on , which states that the manuscript was produced at Rome ( Avril (1972)
) and could be interpreted as giving the date 1062. Roosval believes that Mlxii is, rather, an abbreviation of 1362, which would fit with the dating of the decoration / identified artist ( Roosval (1948)
).

acquisition.p:
The manuscript is listed as no. 10 in Jaches's catalogue of 1695 (U 118:10), with the date on  interpreted as 1112, and as no. 1 in Jaches's catalogue of 1698 (U 122), with the date on  interpreted as 1062. It is listed as no. 1 on shelf 2, bookcase 30, in Hammarsköld's catalogue of the 19th century (U 133). According to Roosval, the manuscript was purchased by Queen Christina in Paris in the middle of the 17th century (
                                    Roosval (1972)

                                ), but while the manuscript had become part of the Royal Library by , it is not listed in Vossius's catalogue of 1651 (U 202:1).
